    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    "headline": "Disc Stack Centrifuge Lubrication Guide: Oil Types, Intervals & Procedures",
    "description": "Disc stack centrifuge lubrication: correct oil types, change intervals, level checks, and common mistakes. Expert maintenance guide from Dolphin Centrifuge.",
    "author": { "@type": "Person", "name": "Sanjay Prabhu MSME", "jobTitle": "Centrifuge Applications Engineer", "worksFor": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "Dolphin Centrifuge" } },
    "publisher": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "Dolphin Centrifuge", "url": "https://dolphincentrifuge.com" },
    "datePublished": "2021-05-01",
    "url": "https://dolphincentrifuge.com/disc-stack-centrifuge-lubrication/",
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What type of oil is used in a disc stack centrifuge?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Alfa Laval recommends an ISO VG 220 gear oil (viscosity index greater than 92) for their disc stack centrifuge main sump. Recommended brands include Castrol Alpha ZN 220, Mobil DTE Oil BB, Shell Tellus C 220, and Texaco Regal R&O 220. Using the wrong viscosity causes overheating, premature bearing wear, and gear damage. Always consult the machine manual or the manufacturer for the correct oil specification for your model." }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How often should disc centrifuge oil be changed?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Disc centrifuge main sump oil should be changed every 2,000 operating hours or every 12 months, whichever is earlier. In a new installation or after the change of gear transmission, change the oil after 200 operating hours and clean the gear housing. When the centrifuge is operated for short periods, lubricating oil must be changed every 12 months even if the total operating hours are low. Refer to your model's maintenance manual for exact intervals." }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What happens if a disc centrifuge is run without enough oil?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Running a disc centrifuge with insufficient lubricant causes rapid bearing and gear overheating, leading to bearing failure, gear damage, and potentially complete machine failure. Oil level should be checked at every startup — the sight glass or dip stick should read at the midpoint when the machine is at rest. Low oil level is the leading cause of premature disc centrifuge mechanical failure." }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Can I use synthetic oil in a disc stack centrifuge?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Synthetic gear oils can be used in disc stack centrifuges if they meet the viscosity grade and additive specifications required by the manufacturer. Synthetics offer better thermal stability and longer service intervals than mineral oils. However, always confirm compatibility with seals and materials in your specific machine model before switching, and follow the manufacturer's guidance on drain intervals for synthetic lubricants." }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How do I check oil quality in the field without a lab analysis?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "During a centrifuge shutdown, slowly unscrew the oil drain plug until a small stream of oil begins to flow. Collect this oil in a clear container. Check for: (1) milky or cloudy appearance — indicates water contamination from bowl seal leakage or condensation; (2) metallic particles or dark sludge — indicates bearing or gear wear; (3) very dark or burnt color — indicates overheated or oxidized oil requiring immediate replacement. Replenish the drained oil with fresh oil to the sight glass midpoint." }
      }
    ]
  }
];
