    <!-- FAQ -->
    <div id="faq" class="mt-10 mb-6">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-navy mb-6">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="space-y-3">
        <details class="border-l-4 border-gold/40 bg-white rounded-r-xl shadow-sm overflow-hidden">
          <summary class="px-5 py-4 font-semibold text-navy cursor-pointer hover:bg-gold/5 transition-colors list-none flex items-center justify-between">
            What type of oil is used in a disc stack centrifuge?
            <span class="text-gold ml-2">+</span>
          </summary>
          <div class="px-5 pb-4 text-text text-sm leading-relaxed">
            Alfa Laval recommends an ISO VG 220 gear oil (viscosity index &gt; 92) for their disc stack centrifuge main sump. Recommended brands include Castrol Alpha ZN 220, Mobil DTE Oil BB, Shell Tellus C 220, and Texaco Regal R&amp;O 220. Using the wrong viscosity causes overheating, premature bearing wear, and gear damage. Always consult the machine manual or the manufacturer for the correct specification for your model.
          </div>
        </details>
        <details class="border-l-4 border-gold/40 bg-white rounded-r-xl shadow-sm overflow-hidden">
          <summary class="px-5 py-4 font-semibold text-navy cursor-pointer hover:bg-gold/5 transition-colors list-none flex items-center justify-between">
            How often should disc centrifuge oil be changed?
            <span class="text-gold ml-2">+</span>
          </summary>
          <div class="px-5 pb-4 text-text text-sm leading-relaxed">
            Main sump oil should be changed every 2,000 operating hours or every 12 months, whichever is earlier. In a new installation or after the change of gear transmission, the first oil change should be done after 200 operating hours and the gear housing cleaned. Refer to your model's maintenance manual for exact intervals.
          </div>
        </details>
        <details class="border-l-4 border-gold/40 bg-white rounded-r-xl shadow-sm overflow-hidden">
          <summary class="px-5 py-4 font-semibold text-navy cursor-pointer hover:bg-gold/5 transition-colors list-none flex items-center justify-between">
            What happens if a disc centrifuge is run without enough oil?
            <span class="text-gold ml-2">+</span>
          </summary>
          <div class="px-5 pb-4 text-text text-sm leading-relaxed">
            Running with insufficient lubricant causes rapid bearing and gear overheating, leading to bearing failure, gear damage, and potentially complete machine failure. Oil level should be checked at every startup — the sight glass should read at midpoint when the machine is at rest.
          </div>
        </details>
        <details class="border-l-4 border-gold/40 bg-white rounded-r-xl shadow-sm overflow-hidden">
          <summary class="px-5 py-4 font-semibold text-navy cursor-pointer hover:bg-gold/5 transition-colors list-none flex items-center justify-between">
            Can I use synthetic oil in a disc stack centrifuge?
            <span class="text-gold ml-2">+</span>
          </summary>
          <div class="px-5 pb-4 text-text text-sm leading-relaxed">
            Synthetic gear oils can be used if they meet the viscosity grade and additive specifications required by the manufacturer. Synthetics offer better thermal stability and longer service intervals than mineral oils. Always confirm seal compatibility and follow the manufacturer's guidance on drain intervals for synthetic lubricants.
          </div>
        </details>
        <details class="border-l-4 border-gold/40 bg-white rounded-r-xl shadow-sm overflow-hidden">
          <summary class="px-5 py-4 font-semibold text-navy cursor-pointer hover:bg-gold/5 transition-colors list-none flex items-center justify-between">
            How do I check oil quality in the field without a lab analysis?
            <span class="text-gold ml-2">+</span>
          </summary>
          <div class="px-5 pb-4 text-text text-sm leading-relaxed">
            During a centrifuge shutdown, slowly unscrew the oil drain plug until a small stream of oil begins to flow. Collect in a clear container and check for: milky/cloudy appearance (water contamination), metallic particles or dark sludge (bearing/gear wear), or very dark/burnt color (overheated oil requiring immediate replacement). Replenish the drained oil with fresh oil to the sight glass midpoint.
          </div>
        </details>
      </div>
    </div>

